'''* Article / lecture: Cryptosecession and the limits of taxation: Towards a theory of non-territorial internal exit. By Trent J. MacDonald & Jason Potts. PUBLIC CHOICE SOCIETY CONFERENCE, March 2016'''

URL = https://mesosoupblog.files.wordpress.com/2016/03/cryptosecession-and-the-limitis-of-taxation-towards-a-theory-of-non-territorial-internal-exit-compressed.pdf

=Abstract=

"This paper presents a model of partial internal exit that captures the competitive dynamic between
incumbent and potential governments in a non-territorial political system. This model particularly
applies to the case of ‘cryptosecession’ that appears the most likely avenue for non-territorial
decentralisation to ever eventuate. It demonstrates how fiscal exploitation is reduced and eventually
eliminated as the capability of citizens to move to non-territorial jurisdictions increases. When
interpreted as a model of cryptosecession, it shows how the balance of citizen opacity and
government legibility determines the balance of fiscal exploitation versus equivalence."
(https://mesosoupblog.files.wordpress.com/2016/03/cryptosecession-and-the-limitis-of-taxation-towards-a-theory-of-non-territorial-internal-exit-compressed.pdf)

